1. N. 30 (80012) + N.73 (88013 ), both described in petrology report as VIII, are macroscopically very different. N.30 is a homogeneous looking grey stone, apparently worked by flaking. N.73 is grey with fine darker mottling throughout, & seems to have been shaped by pecking. Where heavily ground, N.73 is smooth-surfaced: this is especially so on blade, & to a less extent on + around side & poll edges. Elsewhere, the pecked surface shows through + overall the stone lacks the sine of the fully ground parts of N.73, or the whole surface N.30. The only macroscopic similarly lies in the 'marble-like' surface of the unground stone.

comments:
1. Glos. 3; 84. Evens, Smith & Wallis 1972, p. 254, Fig. 6.
2. W.C.Lucy, 1891. Annual address to the Cotteswold Naturalists' Field Club, read at Gloucester, April the 29th, 1890. Proc. Cott. Nat. F.C. 10, 1-38. p.33 - lists stone implements in Mr. G.B. Wilts' collection, including 4 celts from Andoversford. 90012 is illustrated (Plate II, no.18), but not 90010 or 90011. Of the 4 listed, one other is illustrated - not one of these IX celts. No other information is given than provenance. It seems likely that these come from a collection - perhaps bought in Andovers ford? See also Museum Diary p.73. Evens et al. 1972 (p. 242) do not consider this possibility.

1. Glos. 75; 1460.
